00:00:04.080 --> 00:00:08.900
Sometimes when thinking about space we just
use the word star in general and we just think of

00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:11.880
stars, but there are many different types
of stars.

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:13.700
We're going to take a look at some of those.

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:16.800
One is the main sequence star.

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:26.660
Most stars are a main sequence stars, and
so the majority of stars are main sequence

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:28.680
star so that's just your normal star.

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:34.000
You may not know that the sun is actually
a star, it just happens to be very close to

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.860
Earth so it provides us with heat.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:45.600
The sun is a main sequence star and then we
have red supergiants, that's another type.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:51.160
A star that you're familiar with that's a
red supergiant is Betelgeuse.

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:56.080
(Which isn't really spelled like you think
Betelgeuse would be spelled,

00:00:56.540 --> 00:00:58.220
but it has the same pronunciation.)

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:04.760
To give you an idea of how big these types
of stars are, I'm going to kind of provide an analogy.

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:08.380
